This story is about participant scaffolding for later governed interaction, not about new authority, early mutation, or private-source coupling.

Problem Statement

The developer kit is becoming boundary-literate and operationally usable.

But there is a missing layer between:

connection/read-only usage
and

full recursive governance participation

Without that layer, the next integration phase is likely to go wrong in one of two ways.

Failure Mode 1 — Premature Coupling

The repo starts hardcoding:

contract shapes that are not yet sealed

proof-bundle shapes that may still evolve

endpoint assumptions that belong to platform-side DEV-UX

internal field names or request contracts taken from platform code rather than from boundary surfaces

That makes the external participant fragile and violates the boundary doctrine.

Failure Mode 2 — No Preparation At All

The repo remains only a connection/demo surface, with no structure for:

participant contract posture

local verification

proof bundle assembly

future submission adapters

That makes later recursive-governance integration slower, messier, and harder to explain.

This story exists to avoid both errors.

It prepares the developer kit to participate later, while remaining honest about what is and is not supported now.

Story Scope

This story covers:

participant contract placeholder posture

verification runner scaffolding

proof-bundle shape placeholder aligned to emerging platform expectations

adapter-isolated future integration points

explicit documentation separating supported present flows from proof-ready future flows

repo structure that prepares later contract/proof participation without hardcoding unstable internals

This story does not yet cover:

live contract registration

live proof submission

live promotion participation

full recursive governance closure

final proof schema lock

final participant contract schema lock

mutation-bearing flows

Those remain downstream and platform-dependent.

Non-Goals

This story must not:

claim that proof submission is already supported if it is not

hardcode platform-side draft endpoint contracts as if they are final

invent private shortcuts into unfinished proof surfaces

read private platform source as the canonical proof contract

blur supported read-only flows with future proof-bearing flows

define platform proof law from the participant side

tightly couple the developer kit to volatile internals

This is a proof-ready scaffolding story, not a proof-submission implementation story.

Current Boundary Truth This Story Must Respect

This story must remain grounded in what is already true.

A) The Developer Kit Is an External Participant Repo

It is:

separate from keyhole_platform

boundary-consuming

capabilities-first

context-first

read-only operational today

It must not regress into platform-source intimacy.

B) Platform-Side Contract / Proof Surfaces Are Emerging

The platform-side recursive-governance surfaces are still stabilizing through stories like:

participant contract registry

proof submission pipeline

structured verdict and repair artifacts

So the developer kit must prepare for them, not pretend they are already permanently frozen.

C) Boundary Consumption, Not Boundary Definition

The developer kit must remain a consumer of future contract/proof surfaces.

It must not become the place where those surfaces are authoritatively defined.

D) Current Supported Flows Must Stay Honest

Everything currently live and safe remains:

discovery

auth / identity bootstrap

governed context retrieval

read-only smoke flows

That distinction must remain explicit.

Deliverables
1) Participant Contract Placeholder Posture

Create an explicit placeholder posture for future participant contract material.

This does not mean finalizing the live contract registration flow now.

It means creating a clear, boundary-safe place and structure for answering questions like:

who is this participant

what verification classes might it later claim

what supported environment posture might it later declare

what blast-radius or scope posture might later matter

how should this participant describe itself once platform-side contract surfaces stabilize

This placeholder posture must be clearly marked as:

future-facing

non-authoritative

boundary-consuming

not yet the live registered contract

2) Verification Runner Scaffolding

Create scaffolding for a future verification runner inside the developer kit.

This runner should be structured to later support things like:

local test execution

environment capture

verification result collection

proof material assembly

But it must remain honest about current support.

At this stage, the runner is primarily about:

shape

extension points

adapter boundaries

future integration readiness

not about claiming a sealed platform proof flow already exists.

3) Proof-Bundle Shape Placeholder Aligned to Emerging Platform Expectations

Create a placeholder representation for future proof-bundle assembly.

This should align conceptually with the kinds of data the platform is expected to care about, such as:

participant identity

source reference / commit reference

verification outputs

environment metadata

context references

timestamps / traceability fields

future signature or provenance sections

But this placeholder must be clearly marked as:

provisional

local scaffolding

not a final platform contract

awaiting stabilized boundary surfaces

4) Clear Separation Between Current Supported Flows and Proof-Ready Future Flows

Add documentation and code-structure boundaries that make it obvious what is:

Supported now

capabilities discovery

auth/identity bootstrap

governed context retrieval

read-only smoke path

Prepared for later

participant contracts

verification runner

proof-bundle assembly

verdict-aware recursive participation

This separation is critical to honesty, maintainability, and correct expectations.

5) Adapter-Isolated Future Integration Points

Create explicit adapter or interface boundaries for future:

contract registration

proof submission

verdict retrieval / interpretation

repair-guidance handling

These adapter points must isolate later platform integration so that when DEV-UX surfaces stabilize, the developer kit can connect cleanly without rewiring the whole repo.

Functional Requirements
FR-1 — Explicit Proof-Ready Scaffolding

The developer kit must contain visible, explicit proof-ready scaffolding rather than leaving future participant integration implicit or ad hoc.

FR-2 — Boundary-Consuming Posture

All scaffolding must be clearly marked as boundary-consuming, not boundary-defining.

FR-3 — No Unstable Hardcoding

No unstable platform internals, private request contracts, or volatile source-level assumptions may be hardcoded as if they are final.

FR-4 — Adapter Isolation

Future integration points for contract/proof participation must be isolated behind adapters or equivalent seam boundaries.

FR-5 — Supported vs Future Distinction

The repo must clearly distinguish current supported read-only flows from future proof-bearing flows.

FR-6 — Verification Runner Shape

A verification-runner scaffold must exist with a shape suitable for later local verification and proof assembly.

FR-7 — Proof Placeholder Shape

A proof-bundle placeholder model must exist and must be clearly marked provisional.

FR-8 — Human and Agent Clarity

Docs and repo structure must make the future-proofing posture understandable to both humans and agents.

